101
00:06:04,832 --> 00:06:08,434
narrator: the bison is blessed with the perfect winter coat, 

102
00:06:08,436 --> 00:06:13,105
and now bison fibers are helping
people to endure the cold, too.

103
00:06:13,107 --> 00:06:15,641
processed with polyester strands,       

104
00:06:15,643 --> 00:06:19,044
the fibers are made into insulation for winter coats,  

105
00:06:19,046 --> 00:06:24,516
allowing people to hunker down in frigid winter temperatures. 

106
00:06:24,518 --> 00:06:26,651
♪♪         

107
00:06:26,653 --> 00:06:30,656
these winter coats have been  
insulated with bison fiber fill.

108
00:06:30,658 --> 00:06:33,192
it's a by-product of bison ranching       

109
00:06:33,194 --> 00:06:37,996
and a garment insulation that's
no longer going to waste.   

110
00:06:37,998 --> 00:06:40,666
bison fiber fill is a combination        

111
00:06:40,668 --> 00:06:44,136
of the animal's coarse guard hairs, bison down,    

112
00:06:44,138 --> 00:06:47,272
recycled and low-melt polyester.

113
00:06:47,274 --> 00:06:50,175
technicians load the four fibers separately   

114
00:06:50,177 --> 00:06:52,477
into spiked conveyors.     

115
00:06:52,479 --> 00:06:55,347
the fibers were compressed for shipping.         

116
00:06:55,349 --> 00:07:00,819
so as they're loaded, the fibers
are loosened by hand.     

117
00:07:00,821 --> 00:07:05,491
once loading is complete, an  
operator turns on the conveyors.

118
00:07:05,493 --> 00:07:07,826
the conveyors' protruding pins 

119
00:07:07,828 --> 00:07:09,962
snag the bison-and-polyester strands            

120
00:07:09,964 --> 00:07:12,564
and transport them upward.   

121
00:07:12,566 --> 00:07:17,169
the strands travel under rotating spiked cylinders.   

122
00:07:17,171 --> 00:07:21,507
the cylinders comb the fibers to
open them up and detangle them.

123
00:07:21,509 --> 00:07:24,510
the four different fibers flow into scales,       

124
00:07:24,512 --> 00:07:28,113
which weigh equal portions and are released.       

125
00:07:28,115 --> 00:07:30,649
the fibers drop onto a conveyor

126
00:07:30,651 --> 00:07:35,387
and move into a blender for mixing.          

127
00:07:35,389 --> 00:07:39,658
another vertical conveyor with pins picks up the fibers 

128
00:07:39,660 --> 00:07:41,126
and takes them upward,     

129
00:07:41,128 --> 00:07:44,596
past revolving bars that knock off the excess.   

130
00:07:44,598 --> 00:07:49,268
this ensures an even mass, as the bison-and-polyester fibers 

131
00:07:49,270 --> 00:07:53,739
move between a series of different wire-covered rollers.

132
00:07:53,741 --> 00:07:55,808
this process arranges the fibers

133
00:07:55,810 --> 00:08:00,012
in a parallel orientation and gets rid of any clumps.  

134
00:08:00,014 --> 00:08:04,083
a comb further aligns the bison-and-polyester fibers.

135
00:08:04,085 --> 00:08:07,086
the fibers cling together in a web.           

136
00:08:07,088 --> 00:08:11,957
the web transfers to a wooden slat conveyor.   

137
00:08:11,959 --> 00:08:14,893
a vacuum suctions up loose fibers          

138
00:08:14,895 --> 00:08:19,231
to be recycled back into production.     

139
00:08:19,233 --> 00:08:22,567
an oscillating conveyor layers the fibers       

140
00:08:22,569 --> 00:08:25,970
in a zigzag pattern called "cross lapping."    

141
00:08:25,972 --> 00:08:28,974
♪♪         

142
00:08:28,976 --> 00:08:32,444
cross lapping produces a substantial mat,       

143
00:08:32,446 --> 00:08:37,115
and it also mixes the fibers. 

144
00:08:37,117 --> 00:08:40,319
next, the web lands on another conveyor,      

145
00:08:40,321 --> 00:08:44,389
passing between a series of rollers that compress it.  

146
00:08:44,391 --> 00:08:47,392
this process gives the mixed fibers        

147
00:08:47,394 --> 00:08:52,931
the appropriate mass and height
to produce a uniform batt.   

148
00:08:52,933 --> 00:08:55,333
a sprayer applies an adhesive 

149
00:08:55,335 --> 00:08:59,938
to the bison-and-polyester insulation.          

150
00:08:59,940 --> 00:09:02,608
the adhesive doesn't take right away.          

151
00:09:02,610 --> 00:09:05,744
it will need to be heat-activated.        

152
00:09:05,746 --> 00:09:09,214
the insulation moves into a 300-degree oven,       

153
00:09:09,216 --> 00:09:12,351
which triggers the activation. 

154
00:09:12,353 --> 00:09:16,488
the heat also activates the low-melt polyester strands 

155
00:09:16,490 --> 00:09:19,758
in the insulation.       

156
00:09:19,760 --> 00:09:23,295
this bonds the interlaced fibers
to prevent them        

157
00:09:23,297 --> 00:09:27,366
from migrating through fabric when used as fill.       

158
00:09:27,368 --> 00:09:31,703
next, the insulation heads downward into a shearing.   

159
00:09:31,705 --> 00:09:34,706
like a pizza cutter, circular blades        

160
00:09:34,708 --> 00:09:36,975
cut through the center of the insulation mat     

161
00:09:36,977 --> 00:09:39,177
and trim along the edges.   

162
00:09:39,179 --> 00:09:43,715
♪♪         

163
00:09:43,717 --> 00:09:45,783
rollers wind the strips    

164
00:09:45,785 --> 00:09:50,989
of bison fiber and polyester insulation together.      

165
00:09:50,991 --> 00:09:52,991
using a paper cutter,     

166
00:09:52,993 --> 00:09:57,596
an inspector cuts a sample to a specific size.      

167
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:01,066
he weighs the sample      

168
00:10:01,068 --> 00:10:03,869
and confirms that it's adequate for the size,     

169
00:10:03,871 --> 00:10:07,739
verifying the density of the fiber mass.       

170
00:10:07,741 --> 00:10:11,410
next, he measures the sample's thickness.    

171
00:10:11,412 --> 00:10:15,013
at about .13 inches, the fiber fill         

172
00:10:15,015 --> 00:10:18,683
will provide warmth without a lot of bulk.     

173
00:10:18,685 --> 00:10:22,154
the team slices the bison fiber fabric fill  

174
00:10:22,156 --> 00:10:28,093
to its specified length using a hot wire.       

175
00:10:28,095 --> 00:10:32,831
once the roll is complete, they
start rolling the next one.  

176
00:10:32,833 --> 00:10:36,901
the bison fiber rolls are put in plastic bags for protection 

177
00:10:36,903 --> 00:10:41,506
during transport to outside clothing factories.  

178
00:10:41,508 --> 00:10:45,577
technicians weigh each bag separately.          

179
00:10:45,579 --> 00:10:50,182
after several hours, bison fibers and polyester strands  

180
00:10:50,184 --> 00:10:54,386
have been transformed into moisture wicking insulation.  

181
00:10:54,388 --> 00:10:56,855
stuffed inside a jacket liner, 

182
00:10:56,857 --> 00:10:59,958
this bison fiber insulation won't be seen.         

183
00:10:59,960 --> 00:11:01,593
but on a winter day,      

184
00:11:01,595 --> 00:11:04,462
its presence will definitely be felt.    

185
00:11:04,464 --> 00:11:06,431
♪♪         

186
00:11:14,008 --> 00:11:18,409
♪♪         

187
00:11:18,411 --> 00:11:21,480
narrator: shuffleboard originated in british taverns 

188
00:11:21,482 --> 00:11:23,081
in the 15th century.      

189
00:11:23,083 --> 00:11:26,417
players would slide coins, called groats, down the bar,  

190
00:11:26,419 --> 00:11:29,621
aiming for them to stop as close
to the edge as possible    

191
00:11:29,623 --> 00:11:31,423
without falling off.      

192
00:11:31,425 --> 00:11:34,893
it was so popular that     
king henry viii banned the game,

193
00:11:34,895 --> 00:11:38,764
saying it was too much of a distraction from work.  

194
00:11:38,766 --> 00:11:42,100
centuries after shuffleboard was invented,         

195
00:11:42,102 --> 00:11:45,770
this easy and entertaining game
is making a comeback.     

196
00:11:45,772 --> 00:11:50,441
to make a shuffleboard table, 
a technician trims maple strips.

197
00:11:50,443 --> 00:11:52,510
the strips vary in length,   

198
00:11:52,512 --> 00:11:55,714
but they all have the same width
and thickness.         

199
00:11:55,716 --> 00:11:58,917
using a rolling wheel fused with glue,        

200
00:11:58,919 --> 00:12:01,853
the technician applies adhesive
to the strips.         

201
00:12:01,855 --> 00:12:04,055
these strips have grooves on one side    

202
00:12:04,057 --> 00:12:07,326
and protrusions on the other so that they can interlock.  

203
00:12:07,328 --> 00:12:08,860
the glue will ensure      

204
00:12:08,862 --> 00:12:11,797
the interlocked strips stay together.         

205
00:12:11,799 --> 00:12:15,801
after he assembles the strips, he counts them to confirm   

206
00:12:15,803 --> 00:12:21,006
that he has the correct number for the playfield size.    

207
00:12:21,008 --> 00:12:26,445
he lowers a curing press, then clamps the strips together.  

208
00:12:27,748 --> 00:12:30,415
the press applies applies high-temperature heat     

209
00:12:30,417 --> 00:12:34,686
to rapidly cure the glue joints.

210
00:12:34,688 --> 00:12:38,156
the slabs are stored in racks for 30 days          

211
00:12:38,158 --> 00:12:40,492
so that they acclimate to each other.         

212
00:12:40,494 --> 00:12:45,163
once the process is complete, the slabs go into a planer.  

213
00:12:45,165 --> 00:12:50,368
the planer removes dried glue, smooths and levels the surface.

214
00:12:50,370 --> 00:12:53,971
on the left is a slab before it went through the planer,  

215
00:12:53,973 --> 00:12:57,975
and on the right is the one that's had the work done.   

216
00:12:57,977 --> 00:13:00,979
a technician applies adhesive-backed strips     

217
00:13:00,981 --> 00:13:02,781
to mark the score zones    

218
00:13:02,783 --> 00:13:05,850
and tapes the ends to prevent peeling.      

219
00:13:05,852 --> 00:13:08,320
he smooths down the number decals       

220
00:13:08,322 --> 00:13:11,456
that will designate the scoring zones.       

221
00:13:11,458 --> 00:13:14,793
the company logo goes in the center.         

222
00:13:14,795 --> 00:13:18,797
next, a coat of polymer varnish
is applied to the board.    

223
00:13:18,799 --> 00:13:23,135
the varnish encases the decals,
making them resistant to wear. 

224
00:13:23,137 --> 00:13:26,804
the parts of the cradle base are built with plywood.    

225
00:13:26,806 --> 00:13:29,207
a router cuts slots in the base

226
00:13:29,209 --> 00:13:32,344
for the playfield adjustment parts.       

227
00:13:32,346 --> 00:13:35,414
♪♪         

228
00:13:35,416 --> 00:13:38,549
a technician joins two sections of the base    

229
00:13:38,551 --> 00:13:41,286
and builds the cradle skirting.

230
00:13:41,288 --> 00:13:44,156
♪♪         

231
00:13:44,158 --> 00:13:48,093
he adds a piece in the center for extra support,       

232
00:13:48,095 --> 00:13:50,762
links sideboards to the ends, 

233
00:13:50,764 --> 00:13:57,035
and staples the corners together.           

234
00:13:57,037 --> 00:13:59,037
he turns the cradle over    

235
00:13:59,039 --> 00:14:01,973
and screws the skirt to the base from the top,   

236
00:14:01,975 --> 00:14:03,575
beginning at the corners    

237
00:14:03,577 --> 00:14:06,911
and continuing along the entire border.       

238
00:14:06,913 --> 00:14:10,382
he uses rounded maple corners for the end frames       

239
00:14:10,384 --> 00:14:14,119
to eliminate sharp angles.   

240
00:14:14,121 --> 00:14:16,320
he sprays a generous amount of glue            

241
00:14:16,322 --> 00:14:17,989
on the outside of the frame.  

242
00:14:17,991 --> 00:14:22,928
this prepares it to receive a laminated composite material.

243
00:14:22,930 --> 00:14:27,065
he coats the back of the laminate with glue...  

244
00:14:27,067 --> 00:14:30,067
♪♪         

245
00:14:30,069 --> 00:14:32,871
...and wraps the laminate around the end frame,     

246
00:14:32,873 --> 00:14:37,676
which adds a different aesthetic.     

247
00:14:37,678 --> 00:14:39,744
then he sands the rims     

248
00:14:39,746 --> 00:14:42,814
so that it sits evenly on the base of the cradle.   

249
00:14:42,816 --> 00:14:46,617
he glues the end frame to the cradle...        

250
00:14:46,619 --> 00:14:52,624
reinforces the glued seams with staples...        

251
00:14:52,626 --> 00:14:56,027
and joins the sides of the cradle to the end piece,

252
00:14:56,029 --> 00:14:58,629
which fit together perfectly. 

253
00:14:58,631 --> 00:15:01,967
♪♪         

254
00:15:01,969 --> 00:15:06,771
another technician sands the wood until it's silky smooth. 

255
00:15:06,773 --> 00:15:09,841
♪♪         

256
00:15:09,843 --> 00:15:12,710
then a stain is sprayed on the sides of the cradle   

257
00:15:12,712 --> 00:15:14,712
and the skirting.       

258
00:15:14,714 --> 00:15:17,382
the stain enhances the grain of the maple          

259
00:15:17,384 --> 00:15:20,117
and adds a depth of color.   

260
00:15:20,119 --> 00:15:22,987
♪♪         

261
00:15:22,989 --> 00:15:26,057
he sprays on lacquer, which seals the stain     

262
00:15:26,059 --> 00:15:29,294
and gives the wood a glossy finish.        

263
00:15:31,865 --> 00:15:37,536
he adds wooden inlays for visual interest.      

264
00:15:37,538 --> 00:15:42,474
next, the cradle is sprayed with glue.     

265
00:15:42,476 --> 00:15:46,011
a technician applies the carpet
to the glued areas.      

266
00:15:46,013 --> 00:15:48,880
the carpet will absorb the impact of pucks      

267
00:15:48,882 --> 00:15:50,815
that fall off the board.    

268
00:15:50,817 --> 00:15:54,619
with the second end plate   
installed and the legs attached,

269
00:15:54,621 --> 00:15:58,957
the cradle is ready      
for the playfield to be mounted.

270
00:15:58,959 --> 00:16:01,225
the playfield is so heavy,   

271
00:16:01,227 --> 00:16:06,698
it takes two people to lower it
into the cradle.        

272
00:16:06,700 --> 00:16:10,368
this shuffleboard table is now complete.         

273
00:16:10,370 --> 00:16:13,237
even though it's taken three days to build,      

274
00:16:13,239 --> 00:16:17,409
this shuffleboard is worth every bit of hard work.    

275
00:16:26,920 --> 00:16:31,322
♪♪         

276
00:16:31,324 --> 00:16:33,925
narrator: the hallmark of a quality knife       

277
00:16:33,927 --> 00:16:36,194
is a cutting edge that remains sharp       

278
00:16:36,196 --> 00:16:38,863
despite repeated use over time.

279
00:16:38,865 --> 00:16:41,466
one of the most advanced knife-making methods      

280
00:16:41,468 --> 00:16:42,934
is friction forging --     

281
00:16:42,936 --> 00:16:46,470
a technique applied specifically
to the knife's cutting edge  

282
00:16:46,472 --> 00:16:51,142
to produce sharpness and durability.        

283
00:16:51,144 --> 00:16:53,411
friction-forged blades     

284
00:16:53,413 --> 00:16:56,080
are used primarily in hunting and fishing     

285
00:16:56,082 --> 00:16:59,016
but also work just as well in the kitchen.        

286
00:16:59,018 --> 00:17:02,954
the blades are made of high-carbon steel.     

287
00:17:02,956 --> 00:17:06,358
a laser cutter slices out rectangular bars,       

288
00:17:06,360 --> 00:17:09,294
each of which will yield two to five blades.      

289
00:17:09,296 --> 00:17:12,096
the bars are wrapped in foil and put in an oven       

290
00:17:12,098 --> 00:17:16,634
at 1,850 degrees fahrenheit for several hours.       

291
00:17:16,636 --> 00:17:19,571
the heat hardens the steel.  

292
00:17:19,573 --> 00:17:23,040
♪♪         

293
00:17:23,042 --> 00:17:25,977
the bars are removed from the oven and cooled.   

294
00:17:25,979 --> 00:17:27,512
then they're put back in the oven          

295
00:17:27,514 --> 00:17:29,847
and heated to 700 degrees fahrenheit   

296
00:17:29,849 --> 00:17:31,382
for several more hours.    

297
00:17:31,384 --> 00:17:33,184
this second round of heat treating        

298
00:17:33,186 --> 00:17:34,385
tempers the steel,       

299
00:17:34,387 --> 00:17:35,720
drawing down its hardness   

300
00:17:35,722 --> 00:17:39,457
to between 38 and 42 on the rockwell scale.     

301
00:17:39,459 --> 00:17:42,861
the bars are placed on a large electromagnet.   

302
00:17:42,863 --> 00:17:44,663
the magnet holds them securely,

303
00:17:44,665 --> 00:17:47,866
while the bars rotate under a grinding stone.    

304
00:17:47,868 --> 00:17:49,868
a steady flow of coolant    

305
00:17:49,870 --> 00:17:52,136
prevents the heat the friction generates     

306
00:17:52,138 --> 00:17:55,006
from changing the hardness of the steel.   

307
00:17:55,008 --> 00:17:57,475
the grinder removes carbon deposits    

308
00:17:57,477 --> 00:17:59,076
caused by the heat treatment, 

309
00:17:59,078 --> 00:18:03,414
along with any surface imperfections.   

310
00:18:03,416 --> 00:18:06,817
a craftsman uses a rockwell hardness tester   

311
00:18:06,819 --> 00:18:09,087
to measure the bar's hardness. 

312
00:18:09,089 --> 00:18:13,758
the machine's needle bears down
until it indents the steel.  

313
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:17,095
a measurement of 41 is right on target       

314
00:18:17,097 --> 00:18:21,132
and within the range of ultra-tough spring steel.  

315
00:18:21,134 --> 00:18:24,169
the bar is now ready to be friction forged.        

316
00:18:24,171 --> 00:18:26,905
the forging machine's specialized tool        

317
00:18:26,907 --> 00:18:28,906
applies immense pressure,   

318
00:18:28,908 --> 00:18:31,710
combined with rotational movement called "stirring,"  

319
00:18:31,712 --> 00:18:34,646
to a specific area of the bar. 

320
00:18:34,648 --> 00:18:37,182
the stirring action creates friction,       

321
00:18:37,184 --> 00:18:39,317
which plasticizes the steel,  

322
00:18:39,319 --> 00:18:42,454
reducing its microscopic grain structures to levels   

323
00:18:42,456 --> 00:18:44,723
no other forging or heat-treating method    

324
00:18:44,725 --> 00:18:46,191
can achieve,          

325
00:18:46,193 --> 00:18:48,726
50 to 75 times smaller     

326
00:18:48,728 --> 00:18:52,997
than that of the steel typically
used in a high-quality knife. 

327
00:18:52,999 --> 00:18:56,668
the finer the grain size, the stronger the steel,    

328
00:18:56,670 --> 00:18:59,003
the sharper and less brittle the blades           

329
00:18:59,005 --> 00:19:02,674
the unforged zone becomes the blade's main body.     

330
00:19:02,676 --> 00:19:04,942
this area is the tough spring steel,   

331
00:19:04,944 --> 00:19:09,213
with a rockwell hardness between 38 and 42.       

332
00:19:09,215 --> 00:19:13,284
the friction-forged zone becomes
the blade's cutting edge --  

333
00:19:13,286 --> 00:19:16,955
65 to 70 on the rockwell scale.

334
00:19:19,226 --> 00:19:24,162
a computer-guided grinding machine shapes the blade.   

335
00:19:24,164 --> 00:19:27,231
this is what the blade looks like before grinding... 

336
00:19:27,233 --> 00:19:30,235
and after.           

337
00:19:30,237 --> 00:19:33,905
the blade is shotblasted with fine ceramic beads    

338
00:19:33,907 --> 00:19:36,641
to remove all surface imperfections.   

339
00:19:36,643 --> 00:19:40,978
the forged zone is now clearly distinguishable.    

340
00:19:40,980 --> 00:19:44,516
a craftswoman assembles the knife's handle.      

341
00:19:44,518 --> 00:19:47,652
she places a stainless steel bolster over the blade     

342
00:19:47,654 --> 00:19:50,788
and inserts two pins made of nickel silver.     

343
00:19:50,790 --> 00:19:52,991
she trims the pins,      

344
00:19:52,993 --> 00:19:57,061
then flattens them with a hammer
to lock in the bolster.    

345
00:19:57,063 --> 00:19:59,664
♪♪         

346
00:19:59,666 --> 00:20:01,933
here is the blade before...  

347
00:20:01,935 --> 00:20:03,734
and after this assembly.    

348
00:20:03,736 --> 00:20:06,671
a laser engraves the model and brand name    

349
00:20:06,673 --> 00:20:09,073
in the unforged area.     

350
00:20:09,075 --> 00:20:12,076
♪♪         

351
00:20:12,078 --> 00:20:16,814
the craftsman applies glue on both halves of the handles, 

352
00:20:16,816 --> 00:20:18,750
then presses them together.  

353
00:20:18,752 --> 00:20:21,686
this model is made of desert ironwood       

354
00:20:21,688 --> 00:20:24,956
held together with glue and brass nickel pins.     

355
00:20:24,958 --> 00:20:27,025
once the glue dries,      

356
00:20:27,027 --> 00:20:30,295
a craftswoman runs the handle against a sanding belt     

357
00:20:30,297 --> 00:20:33,565
to shape the wood to the steel.

358
00:20:35,168 --> 00:20:40,037
she polishes the wood to bring out the beauty of the grain.  

359
00:20:40,039 --> 00:20:46,310
♪♪         

360
00:20:46,312 --> 00:20:50,981
then the blade is hand-sharpened
on a belt grinder.       

361
00:20:50,983 --> 00:20:53,050
first, the main cut.      

362
00:20:53,052 --> 00:20:55,920
then the edge.         

363
00:20:55,922 --> 00:20:58,856
which stays sharp 10 to 50 times longer     

364
00:20:58,858 --> 00:21:02,226
than a traditionally heat-treated blade.      

365
00:21:03,330 --> 00:21:06,330
finally, the knife is run through a test     

366
00:21:06,332 --> 00:21:08,132
for edge sharpness.      

367
00:21:08,134 --> 00:21:11,335
if the reading indicates the sharpness of a razor blade,  

368
00:21:11,337 --> 00:21:14,672
the friction-forged knife passes the test.        

369
00:21:14,674 --> 00:21:16,574
♪♪         

